    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-03-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-03-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="365"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d365">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">741.5 <gloss target="#t_MSP1"
                    >MSP</gloss>/3–1152</note>
                <head>No. 365<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_CHURCHILLWS1" type="from"
                            >Churchill</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_TRUMANHS1"
                            type="to">Truman</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d365fn1">This message was delivered to Secretary <persName
                            corresp="#p_ACHESOND1">Acheson</persName> by Ambassador <persName
                            corresp="#p_FRANKSSOS1">Franks</persName> on Mar. 11 and was attached to
                        a memorandum by <persName corresp="#p_BATTLELD1">Battle</persName> to the
                        White House, along with <persName corresp="#p_EDENA1">Eden</persName>’s
                        message to <persName corresp="#p_ACHESOND1">Acheson</persName> (<hi
                            rend="italic">infra</hi>), which asked that they be cabled to President
                            <persName corresp="#p_TRUMANHS1">Truman</persName> who was then in
                        Florida.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-03-10">March 10,
                            1952</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>You will no doubt have seen what has been happening over here and I am sure you
                    will be interested in the Budget. Our defense programme is already somewhat
                    spread out. It is not certain that even with a struggle we shall be able to
                    fulfill it. I quite understand you have your difficulties as well as we. When I
                    was over with you there was much talk of “offshore purchases” which could help
                    the <gloss target="#t_NATO1">N.A.T.O.</gloss> front and enable us to fulfill our
                        programme.<note n="2" xml:id="d365fn2">For documentation on the <persName
                            corresp="#p_TRUMANHS1">Truman</persName>–<persName
                            corresp="#p_CHURCHILLWS1">Churchill</persName> talks, held Jan. 5–18, at
                        Washington, see <ref target="#d311">Documents 311</ref> ff.</note>
                </p>
                <p>It would be possible for me to arrange for Canberra and Venom aircraft of the
                    latest types now being made by us in the United Kingdom to be delivered to the
                    United States and distributed by you to <gloss target="#t_NATO1"
                        >N.A.T.O.</gloss> wherever <persName corresp="#p_EISENHOWER1"
                        >Eisenhower</persName> thought they could be most useful.</p>
                <p>If as I hope, you think these ideas are worth pursuing I suggest that our people
                    should talk to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BATTWL1">Batt</persName> in London and
                    that <persName corresp="#p_FRANKSSOS1">Franks</persName> should discuss the
                    matter with <persName corresp="#p_HARRIMANWA1">Averell Harriman</persName>.</p>
                <p>Thank you for what you said about the little package of meat.</p>
                <p>A memo follows.<note n="3" xml:id="d365fn3">Not printed; the <hi rend="italic"
                            >aide-mémoire</hi>, dated Mar. 12, presented a detailed proposal for the
                        United States to accept several hundred jet aircraft from the United
                        Kingdom, thus earning dollars for the British and easing their balance of
                        payments problem. (741.5 <gloss target="#t_MSP1">MSP</gloss>/3–1252)</note>
                </p>
            </div>
        </body>
